[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Scale 2. This is the new version of the animation framework developed by Tingua University and Z.AI. Z.ai. You might know them. They\'re the team behind GLM, one of the popular openweight large language model. They'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also released COG video X and Scale 2. This is the updated model for character animations that you can use without any skeleton pose or control net to transfer character motions from your reference'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video directly into your output video. Take a look at these few examples here. I\'m not going to show each one individually, but you can take a reference from those animations. It looks pretty nice, better than what we had before when we were talking about'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scale one or the scale preview versions. Like last year, we talked about this model when it first released. And back then, it was using 3D pose control as well. But in version two, right now, it\'s even better with a new approach of'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'motion transfer. Instead, it\'s using model specific rope and in contact mass conditions. These two techniques are pretty cool. And as you may have noticed from some of the other AI models out'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there, especially the recent ones for videotovideo editing, rope has been showing up a lot. So this stands for rotary position embedding. And what this does is it allows the diffusion model to transfer motions. Like for example, here'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ve got a motion reference and it gets transferred exactly into the newly generated output even with multiple characters. And another thing, it doesn\'t just support human characters anymore. It supports animals as well. So'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to play around with scale 2 in Comfy UI. As soon as this model dropped, on the first day it launched, it already had Comfy UI support. There are FP16, FP8, and FP8 MX models'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'available. So, depending on what kind of precision your machine can handle, you download whichever one works for you. For the text encoder and VAE, it\'s using the one 2.1 VAE. You can also download'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that from HuggingFace. Just go search for one 2.1 repo and you\'ll see there\'s a split files folder with the text encoder VAE and clip vision that you\'re going to need. Now there\'s also the'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'light x2vora model that\'s required to run scale 2 with low sampling steps because scale 2 can run with the light x2 vora at as few as four steps. So once you\'ve downloaded'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all the models and updated comfy UI, in my case I\'m running on gitpole, you\'ll see the indicator that a new native node that supports scale 2 has been included. Having this, you can start building your'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'comfy UI workflow. So based on the example workflow, I\'ve been using it and playing around with it a bit. I\'ve tried out different video animations, different video editing tasks using this workflow. And as you'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see, there\'s a new native node in here. We\'ve got the one scale two to video node. This is what handles the scale 2 conditions. You pass in the conditions v a pose video pose video'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mask reference image reference image mask and clip vision. All required to run this model. For the previous frame and video frame offset, those are used'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for video extension. That means you can extend the video beyond 81 frames. While 81 frames is the preset default for each sampler run on the Juan video 2.1 models. With video extension like this,'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can stitch everything together. Kind of like some of the videos I showed you a long time ago about Juan 2.1 vase and one 2.2 vase. Those were also able to stitch together with overlapping frames'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you could keep extending to make longer videos. So basically you pass the previous frame data from the first sampler. Now back to sampler part one here. This generates the first 81 frames from the beginning of the video to video'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation. So how does the replacement mode work? First of all, this is a boolean. So it\'s either true or false. In my workflow setup, I\'ve put a control switch here.'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So if I set this to true, then it triggers the scale to video native node to set replacement mode to true. What this means is the character will replace an existing video element. So in here'

[04:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ve got this video footage of a singer dancing on stage and I\'m going to swap only this character as a replacement. So I pass in this image as my reference image for the character I want to swap'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into that video. Now in this case if I set replacement to true and the mode is set to replace character rather than background then the video will show white backgrounds for the masked areas'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because we\'re using the SAM 3 video tracker. Now this is a new node right here create scale 2 color masks. These color masks allow the scale model to detect the conditions that it needs to'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate in the video output. So, for example, if you have multiple objects, characters, animals, whatever you want to swap, they\'ll each be indicated by different colors in the mask. So, the blue color represents the person'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'singing. I have this image as the reference image. The model detects that this character needs to replace the singer in the video. So, the output looks like this. As you can see, the guy has been swapped with the reference'

[05:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image. and side by side you can clearly understand why it\'s called replacement mode. It replaces the masked objects from the process and puts them into the video. Now notice something. This video'

[05:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to video editing has no control net DW pose to mimic character motion, no depth map, nothing like that. It\'s purely based on the scale 2 color mask for generating the mask. And because the'

[05:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scale 2 model has in context learning and the rope technique that we talked about, it\'s able to transfer character motions movement to the new reference image character and put that into the'

[06:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'output video like this. So that\'s the unique feature of this model. And as you can see, this is using the one 2.1 model settings because scale 2 is also based'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the 1 2.114b model. That\'s why we can use one 2.1 light x2v for the distillation sampling in this workflow. The scheduler I\'m testing with six steps. You can try four'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'steps, eight steps or even higher, but six steps is generally a good sweet spot for using light x2v in video generation like this. So the whole setup is ready to go. Now let\'s try something else. In the max object setting, you can set not'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just one but two or three even higher numbers. That means you can control how many objects the model detects in the input video or the mask from your reference image. Because in here'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can see the SAM 3 tracking. One track for the driving data which is the video input and another for the reference track which comes from the reference image.'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
