[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frames to match with your reference video. In this video, you can see different camera angles moving around. The characters aren\'t just standing there statically. There\'s a lot of motion, some boxing practice, and you\'ll'

[07:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see some body parts of the left and right characters overlap in the camera view. Scale 2 can handle this. I\'m using this image of two characters. Now, these two characters, I created them'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'previously for other AI video content. This one represents the character on the left, and this one represents the character on the right. So, I\'m using this video as the motion reference. The first frames get passed into DW pose'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because I need to generate this image using QuinnEdit. Now, you could use other image editing models, but for getting video first frames and editing them, I usually go with Quenedit. The prompt is basically replace the image of'

[08:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this man identify both characters in the boxing match. And that\'s how we get the start frame based on the DW pose reference. By doing this, we get this image here that can be used for the'

[08:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video first frame. Coming back to the first frame, it\'s the same pose as our reference image. So this time, let\'s say I want to replace the entire background as well. We\'re only capturing the motions of the two characters in the'

[08:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'boxing ring and the camera motions. how the camera follows the character movements for the segmentation. Since we\'re using SAM 3.1 and I\'ve talked about SAM 3.1 before, video tracking is'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of the data types it supports and now it\'s natively integrated with scale 2 in comfy UI. That\'s great because we can use SM3 video tracking data directly. I set the condition to detect'

[09:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the two fighters in the boxing match. So max objects is set to two and I\'m using the same video track for the reference image. Let\'s run this and see how it looks. So here\'s the segmentation result. We\'ve got two different colored'

[09:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'objects here, blue and red. That\'s how the scale 2 video model identifies which character belongs to which reference image for the swap. And that\'s how it tracks those motions and transfers them to the new reference image characters.'

[09:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In this test case, I also used a for loop for video extension because once you have the first sampling run and you pass the first 81 frames along with the video frame offset into the for loop,'

[09:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you set the number of loops based on the total frame count. Then we do some math to figure out how many 81 frame batches we still need. The video offset gets passed into the next input, which is'

[09:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what I mentioned at the beginning, and it loops continuously. The output offset feeds back into the loop end and it cycles through. Now, we\'ve played around with this for'

[10:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'loop concept for a long time on this channel, almost 12 months ago now when I first introduced this unlimited loop concept. Man, time goes fast. The technology has evolved, but the concept is still the same. Eventually, if you\'re'

[10:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'making long- form video, you need to extend it over multiple sampling passes. And the same concept applies here. All the data gets passed through, including previous image frames, and it gets'

[10:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stacked together. It stitches with the previous images plus the newly generated 81 frames. Those video frames go through the loop and then to the video output. I also put a comparison node in here just for'

[10:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'testing. If you don\'t want that, you can bypass the comparison with your reference video and you\'ll only get the generated video output without the reference video playing alongside it. Okay, so here\'s the first batch, 81'

[10:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frames. Then it passes through the loop going through five loop cycles. The math works out. So five total passes and we get the full frame count matching the'

[11:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference video. As you can see, the two characters are here. the motions from the reference are being transferred perfectly. But one thing I forgot to turn on was the replacement mode for full background replacement. So I\'ll'

