[13:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all of those are being transferred. Let me put this side by side with the three videos and the reference image. The slight camera movements in the background, those are also captured. The'

[13:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eyebrow movements looking up and down, motions from the realistic footage, all mimicked in the output. I think Scale 2 does a really solid job for video motion'

[13:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transfer. And we\'re not talking about control net here anymore. You know, for diffusion transformer models in 2026. Control net is kind of old school at this point. Look at what we\'ve seen recently with Bernini and Scale 2.'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They\'re not using DW pose or depth map control net to track and mimic character motions anymore. They\'re using their own techniques like this 3D rope approach to capture the full video motion and'

[13:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transfer it into the new output. This is the direction we\'re heading. AI models are getting more advanced, less work for us, honestly. Less need to chain together all those control net conditions. Look at the conditioning'

[14:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. It\'s basically nothing. Just text prompts. What we need is the segmentation masks from the two input parameters. That\'s it. That\'s all you need for video motion transfer with'

[14:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scale 2. It\'s pretty cool. Although scale 2 is based on one 2.1, which is kind of an older model at this point. After fine-tuning and retraining from the Z.AI team, I would say this model is actually even better than Juan 2.2'

[14:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
